The role has remained steady despite Jalon Walker breaking out, but Ebiketie will need to show more to be considered anything more than an ocean deep league bench stash. Look elsewhere for Week 11.

Brooks stayed hot in Week 10, generating six solos, six assists, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. The Dolphins linebacker has been elite this season and should continue to be counted as a top-three option for a plus Week 11 matchup against Washington.

Wagner continued to produce in Week 10, reeling off a cool six solos and three assists. The veteran linebacker has been a steady LB1 force this season and has been heating up recently, recording six or more solos in two of his last three. Tap Wagner as a top-10 play for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Landman was at it again in Week 10, most recently racking up five solos, six assists, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble on Thursday Night Football. LB1 level production, tap him as a top-15 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Tremaine continued his throwback season in Week 10, notching four solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Edmunds has provided LB1 value this season and should be treated as one for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

Cedric Gray was back at it in Week 9, going off with 11 solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Gray has been elite since Week 4, tallying 41 solos in six games, and has muscled his way into the elite LB2 conversation in the process. Tap him as an LB2 with weekly LB1 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Carson showed up in Week 10, tallying five solos, five assists, 0.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. This was the rookie's first game with more than four solos since back in Week 3, but is hopefully a sign that the game is starting to slow down for him. Treat the rookie linebacker as an LB3 at best despite the plus Week 11 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Kaden Elliss was excellent in Week 10, racking up one solo, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Elliss managed to produce despite the low solo count and remains locked in as a top-tier LB2 option. Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Lavonte was excellent in Week 10, racking up six solos and three assists. David has been a strong LB2 option this season and should be treated as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Carter was excellent in Week 9, tallying five solos, five assists, and one pass defended. The Bengals linebacker has registered five or more solos in every game since supplanting Logan Wilson as the starter. Fire the talented linebacker up as an easy LB2 play, a plus Week 11 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Bolton was excellent in Week 9, notching five solos, nine assists, and one tackle for loss. Bolton is still a top-15 option but has moved closer to the lower end of that spectrum due to frustrating inconsistency. Count him as an LB1 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Eric Wilson continues to produce, most recently tallying five solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Wilson has been one of the most consistent options since stepping into the starting lineup for the Vikings and should be viewed as an elite LB2 option until he cools down. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Drake was at it again in Week 10, stacking four solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Thomas has been an easy LB2 play since stealing the job from Tyrice Knight, but it would surprise most to know that he has actually been the LB8 in fppg since Week 4. While it is not yet time to start treating him as an LB1 for IDP purposes, the weekly upside is obviously there. Start him with confidence everywhere as a sneaky top-15 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Winters was excellent in Week 10, tallying five solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Dee is starting to heat back up after a quiet three game stretch from Week 5 to Week 7. Winters has registered five or more solos in two of his last three games and should be counted as a low floor, high upside LB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

SirVocea showed up in Week 8, racking up four solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Dennis has been on a mini tear for IDP managers, checking in as the LB2 overall over the last three weeks. Count the Buccaneers linebacker as an LB2 option as long as he is cooking. Start SirVocea with confidence in leagues of all sizes.

Watt was excellent in Week 10, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Watt is up to six sacks on the season and has recorded a sack in back-to-back games, a sign that he may finally be inching closer to the dominant pass rusher IDP managers were hoping for. Tap T.J. as a DL1 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Quincy Williams had a mini revenge game on his own team in Week 10, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss on 71 percent of the snaps. He hit Quinnen Williams' signature celebration after recording his sack. The snap count was a major surprise for fantasy managers and Jets fans alike as Quincy was demoted as a starter in favor of journeyman Mykal Walker. Quincy produced despite losing his starting role, and has now strung together back-to-back plus outings since returning from injury. Williams was rumored to be discussed as a package with his brother, Quinnen, to Dallas before they acquired Logan Wilson, but when the Jets realized they were stuck with him, they decided to demote him. The role uncertainty lowers his floor, so treat him as more of a low-end LB2 for Week 11, despite the plus Week 11 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Teddye showed up in Week 10, racking up five solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. Buchanan has played his way into top-25 status since entering the starting lineup and should be treated as an upside LB2 for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Tyrice went off in Week 10, tallying six solos, two assists, two sacks, three tackles for loss, and two forced fumbles. The linebacker got the start with Ernest Jones (knee) sidelined and looked excellent in his spot start, at least IDP production wise. His issues in pass coverage are attributed to why he lost his job to Drake Thomas, and Drake has done nothing to relinquish the role since taking over. Knight is now an elite spot starter if Jones or Thomas miss time.

DFF was excellent in Week 10, racking up five solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Flanningan-Fowles was set to steal the starting job anyway, but is now seeing an even larger role than expected due to Darius Muasau (ankle) being placed on IR. DFF will be inconsistent but has produced over the last two weeks, making him an upside LB3 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Green Bay Packers. Add and start Flannigan-Fowles where needed.

Gibbens was excellent in Week 10, reeling off five solos, five assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Gibbens failed to wrestle the job from Christian Elliss as many expected him to, but got the start for Week 10 due to Ellis dealing with a hip injury. Gibbens will produce when he gets starter's snaps and should be stashed where possible in the event Elliss misses more action. If he gets another start, treat Gibbens as an LB3 with LB2 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against the New York Jets. Stash Gibbens where roster space allows.

Mack was excellent in Week 10, racking up one solo, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble on 73 percent of the snaps. Mack has recorded a sack in three of his last four games and in four of his six games overall. Count Khalil as a DL2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Add Mack wherever available in competitive leagues.

Herbig was excellent in Week 10, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss on 42 percent of the snaps against the Los Angeles Chargers. Herbig is up to 5.5 sacks on the season, but has seen his role dwindle since Alex Highsmith returned from injury. fTap Herbig as a bye week filler DL3 type for Week 11, thanks to a plus Week 11 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Jalon was at it again in Week 10, stacking four solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery on a career high 65 percent of the snaps. Walker is suddenly the LD18 due to massive back-to-back spike weeks and looks to have entered his name into the Rookie Defensive Player of the Year mix in the process. Fire Walker up as an easy DL2 play while he is cooking. Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Tykee was back to doing Tykee things after the Bucs bye, firing off four solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Tykee has been a revelation for fantasy managers this season, parlaying Antonie Winfield's old role into becoming the new DB1 in fantasy football. Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Branch was excellent in Week 10, racking up four solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Branch remains a top-10 option for Week 11, and coming off his second-highest fantasy output of the season, we can be more confident about his weekly floor. Start Branch with confidence for what should be a heavyweight tilt against the Philadelphia Eagles on Sunday Night Football.

Hamilton disappointed in Week 10, managing just one assist and two passes defended. There was hope for the talented safety while he was at free safety, but now that he is in the slot, we will just have to accept that the best safety in the league is not very productive in IDP this year. He can no longer be trusted as a DB1 option. Continue to treat Hamilton as a high upside, low floor DB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Quentin Lake was excellent in Week 10, racking up eight solos and three assists. Lake has been a steady DB1 force this season and should continue to be treated as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks. Tap Lake as a top-15 option everywhere.

Talanoa was excellent in Week 10, reeling off five solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Hufanga has been a steady DB2 option this season, but has started to heat up over his last two, recording four solos and four assists in each. Tap Talanoa as a top-15 option for what should be a busy afternoon against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Bates showed out in Week 10, tallying six solos, three asists, one forced fumble, one interception, and two passes defended. Bates has been a massive IDP disappointment this season, so hopefully this is a sign that he is gearing up for the stretch run. Continue to treat the talented safety as more of a DB2 than a DB1 despite the excellent production against Indianapolis.

Moehrig was excellent in Week 10, racking up six solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. Tre'von hasn't lit the world on fire with his solo count but has still found a way to be consistently productive, thanks to chipping in one sack, nine tackles for loss, one interception, and two passes defended along the way. Treat Moehrig as an elite DB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Emmanwori was excellent in Week 10, tallying five solos, four assists, 0.5 sacks, and four passes defended. The rookie has recorded five solos in back-to-back games and is starting to become an IDP force. There will be some inconsistency for the rookie, but he now has a regular role as he has moved to the slot to make way for Ty Okada, who got the tap at strong safety with Julian Love still dealing with a hamstring injury. Tap Emmanwori as a DB3 with easy DB2 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Bishop was at it again in Week 10, tallying six solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Bishop has now posted back-to-back spike weeks and has solidified himself as a DB2 play in the process. The talented young safety appears to be getting more comfortable in the Bills' defense and is making the type of impact IDP managers expected when he was drafted. Tap Bishop as a top-25 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

CJGJ went bonkers in Week 10, reeling off seven solos, two assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Gardner-Johnson has been a DB1 since being signed by the Bears and should be treated as one for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings. Add and start the talented safety as a top-10 option wherever possible.

Minkah was excellent in Week 10, tallying six solos, one fumble recovery, and one pass defended. Minkah has been a disappointment this season, but has still had some weeks that remind us of why he remains in the DB2 mix. Tap Fitzpatrick as a low floor top-25 option for a neutral-at-best Week 11 matchup against Washington.

Harrison Smith was at it again in Week 10, generating five solos, two assists, and one forced fumble. The veteran safety has provided DB2 value since the Vikings' bye week and should be counted as one for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Smith should be on far more rosters.

Watts showed up in Week 10, racking up six solos and five assists. This was the best fantasy outing since Week for the Falcons safety, who has slipped to become more of a DB2/3 than a DB2 due to his floor. He still has promising upside, as evidenced by his performance from Week 1 to Week 4, when he was the S12 overall, but he needs to become more consistent. Tap Watts as a borderline DB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Malaki Startks showed up in Week 10, notching two solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Starks has been a borderline DB2 option since moving to free safety and should be considered a top-15 option for Week 11, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Jordan Battle showed up in Week 9, tallying five solos and seven assists. Battle was providing solid DB3 value prior to the bye and should be counted as one for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Start Battle where needed.

Ronnie Harrison flashed in Week 10, stacking five solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 45 percent of the snaps. Harrison made an impact in Week 10, but is not playing enough to trust for fantasy purposes. Leave him on waiver wires despite the strong production and the plus Week 11 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

DaRon Bland was excellent in Week 9, racking up six solos, eight assists, and one pass defended. Bland has been making good on his CB1 status and has been pushing his way into the DB2 conversation over his last three games. The DB2 overall during that three game span, Bland can be a difference maker down the stretch. Tap him as a DB3 with obvious DB2 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

McDuffie showed out in Week 9, tallying five solos, seven assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Despite the strong production, McDuffie remains a CB2 at best, as he has struggled for plus outings all season. With that said, he is trending up, as he has recorded four or more solos in three of his last four games. Tap him as a CB2/DB4 type where needed for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Evan Williams was excellent in Week 10, racking up four solos, three assists, and two tackles for loss. Williams has not been much more than a bye week filler for 12-team league purposes, and this performance does little to change that. The Packers safety is a better real life player than fantasy producer, making him someone who should only be on radars in 16+ team leagues. Look elsewhere for your Week 11 DB3.

Malachi Moore showed up in Week 10, reeling off six solos and two assists. Malachi has started to heat up for IDP managers, tallying five or more solos in each of his last two games. Tap Moore as a DB3 option where needed for a plus matchup against the New England Patriots.
